collation.catchwords: Catchwords by several hands and sometimes quire singatures in arabic numerals. The majority have been lost due to trimming.

p.note: Top of page in black ink by a 19th century hand: Kgl. Bibl. 1734 års Kat. Theol. in 4o no 12; below by same hand: Missale; center page in pencil by a modern hand: Troligen från Österrike (Stiftet Salzburg? Obs. Den h. Rupert dag och translatio oo? Virgilius 13 okt Cholomannus, festum duplex!). Säkert från Melk. se bl. 261!!.

binding.p: Medieval binding. Red leather over wooden boards. 3 double raised bands and endbands. Corner pieces and bosses in brass.
binding.decoNote: Blind tooled concentric panels filled with geometrical and vegetative patterns.
binding.condition: Binding heavily damaged. Most of and have been replaced by a modern paper over cardboard binding, which is also damaged. Only the and the parts of the front and back covers closest to the spine are intact. On these parts the leather is heavily worn and repaired.

history.origin: Austria , 15th century The place of origin is based on the inclusion of the saints Rupert, Virgilius and Cholomannus in the calendar and Proper of saints. These saints may point more specifically to Salzburg or Melk, where they were especially venerated.
history.provenance: Early provenance unknown. According to the old library catalogues, the missal has belonged to the National Library since the 17th century. The note on refers to the catalogue of 1734 (U 125e), where it is listed as Theol in 4o no 12.

msItem.title: Blessing of Salt and Water
msItem.rubric: Sequitur Exorcismus Salis et aque dominicis diebus
msItem.explicit: hic et in eterna secula seculorum Amen

msItem.title: Blessing of Wine
msItem.explicit: ut magnitudinem tuam intelligant Per dominum Deinde Aspergatur et Thurificetur

msItem.title: Proper of time
msItem.incipit: AD te leuaui animam meam deus meus (Ps. 24:1)
msItem.explicit: et sanguinis tui temporalis precepcio prefigurat Per
msItem.note: The Proper of time begins with the First Sunday of Advent and the first part ends with Corpus Christi. The Proper of time is continued after the Ordo and Canon missae.

msItem.title: Dedication of an altar
msItem.incipit: Dicit dominus sermones meos quos dedi

msItem.title: Ordo and Canon missae
msItem.explicit: et abii et lauii et vidi et credidi

note.p: : Canon. The leaf that most likely contained the Canon image has been cut out.
: the section that starts with the Canon and continues until the end of the Ordo and Canon missae has a different layout compared to the rest of the manuscript.

msItem.title: Proper of time (continued)
msItem.note: The second part of the Proper of time appears to regress, beginning with the First Sunday after the octave of Easter, while the first part ended with Corpus Christi. It ends with the Twenty-fifth Sunday after the octave of Pentecost.

msItem.title: Proper of saints
msItem.rubric: Incipit liber de sanctis In vigilia sancti Andree

note.p: The Proper of saints begins with the vigil for Saint Andrew (29 November) and ends with Saint Katherine (25 November) and an office for the evangelists.

msItem.title: Common of saints
msItem.explicit: exoramus ut percepti tui sacramenti nos virtute defendas Per

note.p: : common of one confessor and bishop;
: common of one confessor not bishop;
: common of one and many virgins;
: common of a woman neither a virgin, nor a martyr.

msItem.title: Votive masses
msItem.rubric: Incipiunt misse votive per ebdomadam et primo de sancta trinitate
msItem.explicit: Cum sanctis tuis in eternum quia pius es

note.p: Collection of votive masses beginning with the mass for the Trinity.

supportDesc.foliation: medieval foliation in black ink. Errors in foliation: 1-135, 137-191, 191a, 192-225, 227-251, 251a, 252-329.
supportDesc.condition: Parchment stained and dirty in places, e.g. . Holes and tears in the parchment in places, some of which show signs of contemporary repairs, e.g. and . cut out, only stub remains.

p.note: Top of page in black ink by an early modern hand: 1566, 1424, 142, 566.

Occasional marginal and interlinear additions in ink by several medieval hands. They consist of corrections, additions, glossing, and cross-references. Some leaves, e.g. , contain more extensive additions. On there is a longer addition.

A large number of papers slips were originally placed between leaves as pagemarks. These slips contain text written by several contemporary hands. The text, ranging from 1-8 lines, seems to indicate passages on the leaves they were placed between. At some point the slips were removed and are now stored in two envelopes ( and ) attached to . indicate where the slips were previously placed. One slip stilll remains in its original place between . It reads: prosa de Sancta Affra Grates deo et honore.

decoDesc.p: Main text in black ink, rubrics in red, capitals touched in red.
decoDesc.decoNote:
: opening decorated initial A over 7 lines in blue. The initial has reserved interior shapes and is surrounded by a complex flourishing and floral shapes in red. : plain chapter initial E over 6 lines in blue surrounded by a complex flourishing and floral shapes in red. : plain initials over 2-3 lines in red. : plain initials over 1-5 lines in red, some with reserved interior shapes. Some initials, e.g. on , extend into the margin with a flourish. : penwork initials over 2 lines in black, touched in red or with red flourishing.
Besides the main initial scheme consisting of different types of plain red initials and small penwork initials (most frequently on the top line), the manuscript also contains several sets of more idiosyncratic initals: : puzzle initial over 3 lines in red and black. : puzzle initial over 12 lines in red and black. The initial has reserved interior shapes and extends into the margin. : gold initial over 3 lines, placed on a green field.
: plain initials over 2 lines in black ink (perhaps a later addition?). : plain initials over 2 lines alternatig in blue, red, and green. : missing initial. : plain initials over 1 line in green.
Ordo and canon missae: : decorated initial T over 6 lines. The letter body is made up of blue vegetative shapes that extend into a frame; the counterspace is filled in purple with diamonds and circles pattern in gold. From the initials three vines extend into the margins to form a frame. They are painted in purple, yellow and green. : plain initials over 1 line in blue or red.
